definition.value: Any member of the group of lipids containing a common glycerol backbone to which at least one fatty acid-derived group is attached.
An oxoacid containing four carboxy groups.
Any fatty acid containing a ring composed of carbon atoms.
A carboxylic ester in which the carboxylic acid component can be any fatty acid.
Any anion of a tricarboxylic acid  formed by deprotonation of at least one carboxy group.
Any anion of a tetracarboxylic acid formed by deprotonation of one or more carboxy groups.
A carboxylic acid anion formed when the carboxy group of a monocarboxylic acid is deprotonated.
A phosphorus oxoanion that is the conjugate base of phosphoric acid.
Sphinganine, its homologs and stereoisomers, and the hydroxy and unsaturated derivatives of these compounds.
An azole based on a five-membered heterocyclic aromatic skeleton containing one N and one O atom.
Compounds having the nitroso group, -NO, attached to carbon, or to another element, most commonly nitrogen or oxygen.
A tricarboxylic acid monoanion that is the conjugate base of citric acid, obtained by deprotonation of one of the three carboxy groups.
A tricarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of two of the three carboxy groups of citric acid.
An organoarsonic acid where the organyl group is 4-hydroxy-3-nitrophenyl.

Any fatty acid in which the parent hydrocarbon chain has one or more alkyl substituents; a common component in animal and bacterial lipids. The fatty acyl chain is usually saturated and the substituent a methyl group; however, unsaturated BCFAs are found in marine animals, and branches other than methyl are found in microbial lipids.
An organosulfur compound having the structure RS(=O)2R (R =/= H).
Any alpha-amino acid ester that has L-valine as the amino acid component.
Any monocarboxylic acid which also contains a separate (alcoholic or phenolic) hydroxy substituent.
Any monocarboxylic acid having at least one additional oxo functional group.
That isomer of butenoic acid having the double bond at position C-3.
The conjugate base of crotonic acid; used by some bacterial species as a carbon and energy source.
A butenoate having the double bond at the 3-position.
Any carboxylic acid anion containing at least one oxo group.
A dicarboxylic acid monoanion that is the conjugate base of glutaric acid.
Any monocarboxylic acid having a 2-oxo substituent.
A steroid ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of any carboxylic acid with the 3-hydroxy group of a sterol.
A monosubstitution product of hydrogen peroxide, HOOH.
Monosubstitution products of hydrogen peroxide HOOH, having the skeleton ROOH, in which R is any organyl group.
A pentenoate having the double bond at the 4-position.
A pentenoic acid having the double bond at position 4.
A pentenoic acid having the double bond at position 2.
An alpha-amino acid ester of L-lysine.
A hexadienoic acid with double bonds at C-2 and C-4; it has four geometrical isomers, of which the trans,trans-form is naturally occurring.
A pentadienoic acid with the double bonds at positions 2 and 4.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that has a hydroxy group beta to the carboxy group.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid which has hydroxy group located gamma to the carboxy group.
An oxo monocarboxylic acid anion having the oxo group located at the 3-position (R = H or organyl group).
